  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins on 'Marty Supreme,' Josh Safdie's Timothée Chalamet ping-pong picture, then Sean's long conversation with Safdie about how he made it.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Marty Supreme’",
      "note": "Sean and Amanda on the year's ping-pong picture",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Marty Supreme",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Josh Safdie's first solo feature (co-written and co-edited with Ronald Bronstein, shot by Darius Khondji, scored by Daniel Lopatin) casts Timothée Chalamet as Marty Mauser, a fast-talking 1950s New York table-tennis hustler loosely based on ping-pong legend Marty Reisman. Both hosts love it (it was No. 2 on Amanda's movies-of-the-year list) and read it as an Uncut Gems companion that, by going period, turns the Safdie anxiety into something more fable-like and open-hearted: a movie about ambition, confidence, and growing up that ends on the birth of Marty's son. They single out Chalamet (Pacino/Ad-Rock energy), a shockingly good Kevin O'Leary as pen magnate Milton, Gwyneth Paltrow as faded movie star Kay Stone, Odessa A'zion as Rachel, and Abel Ferrara, Fran Drescher, Tyler the Creator, and Penn Jillette in the deep bench. The 1950s setting runs on 1980s needle drops: Forever Young over the opening credits, Everybody Wants to Rule the World over the ending. They walk through the box-office stakes for an expensive A24 original (tracking 36-57 domestic) and its Oscar odds: Best Picture and Chalamet likely, score a must, directing a long shot in a crowded field."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Josh Safdie",
      "guest": "Josh Safdie on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Marty Supreme",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Safdie's first time on the show since Uncut Gems in 2019. He traces the film to a dime-store book his wife found (Marty Reisman's 'Confessions of a Table Tennis Champion and Hustler') and to his own uncle Johnny, who played at Lawrence's, the first Black-owned business in the Times Square district. He talks through the postmodern logic of scoring a 1950s film with 1980s music (the '80s were already doing the '50s), Daniel Lopatin's orchestral-plus-synthetic score, and his casting-as-iconography method: real histories drafted into the roles (Kevin O'Leary as an 'iconic asshole,' Abel Ferrara as a New York street heavy, Tyler the Creator improvising period slang). He describes the ending (meeting your child) as the emotional core, and a cut Tears for Fears-concert coda that survives only as the 'Everybody Wants to Rule the World' drop."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Borrower",
          "year": 1991,
          "note": "Safdie's last great thing: John McNaughton's sci-fi horror about an alien sentenced to live on Earth as a human, whose borrowed heads keep exploding, forcing it to rip off and swap new ones. He watched it the night before to unwind, prizing its skid-row realism and its kinship with The Thing and The Hidden (all three, he notes, have the creature take a dog's head)."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
